column3: ” a young black man (Daniel Kaluuya) finds himself in a very messed up situation —actually a massive understatement — when he goes out to the country to visit his white girlfriend’s (Allison Williams) family. We won’t give anything else away
column4: but if you’ve seen the trailer
column5: you can get a hint of how Peele created a unique chiller that explores real ideas and attitudes about race
column6: some of them quite ugly. But he won’t be done with that movie
column7: apparently.. more are coming.  From Jason Guerrasio:  But this is far from a one-and-done for Peele. He recently told Business Insider that “Get Out” is the first in a collection of movies he wants to direct that examine what he calls “social demons.” “I have four other social thrillers that I want to unveil in the next decade
column8: ” Peele told Business Insider. “The best and scariest monsters in the world are human beings and what we are capable of especially when we get together. I’ve been working on these premises about these different social demons
column9: these innately human monsters that are woven into the fabric of how we think and how we interact
column10: and each one of my movies is going to be about a different one of these social demons.” Peele’s examination of race and alienation in “Get Out” is an impressive
column11: confident directorial debut. We can’t wait to see what he will throw at us next
column12: though we’re also pretty afraid.  " False link
